{{ infobox disease | Name = Hyperthecosis | Image = | Alt = | Caption = | DiseasesDB = | ICD10 =E28.8 | ICD9 = {{ICD9|256.8}} | ICDO = | OMIM = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeshID = | GeneReviewsID = | GeneReviewsName = }} '''Hyperthecosis''' (or ovarian hyperthecosis) is [[hyperplasia]] of the [[theca interna]] of the [[ovary]].<ref>Taber's Cyclopedic Medical Dictionary 21st Edition</ref> Hyperthecosis occurs when an area of luteinization occurs along with stromal hyperplasia. The luteinized cells produce [[androgens]], which may lead to [[hirsutism]] and [[virilization]] (or masculinization) in affected women.<ref>Stead, Stead, Kaufman, Suarez (2009). First Aid for the Obstretrics & Gynecology Clerkship - Second Edition. McGraw-Hill</ref>
The term hyperthecosis refers to the presence of nests of luteinized theca cells in the ovarian stroma due to differentiation of the ovarian interstitial cells into steroidogenically active luteinized stromal cells. These nests or islands of luteinized theca cells are scattered throughout the stroma of the ovary, rather than being confined to areas around cystic follicles as in [[Polycystic ovary syndrome|polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)]]. These luteinized theca cells result in greater production of androgens.
Seen as a severe form of PCOS, the clinical features of hyperthecosis are similar to those of PCOS.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Cunxian|last2=Sung|first2=C. James|last3=Quddus|first3=M. Ruhul|last4=Simon|first4=Rochelle A.|last5=Jazaerly|first5=Tarek|last6=Lawrence|first6=W. Dwayne|date=2017-01-01|title=Association of ovarian hyperthecosis with endometrial polyp, endometrial hyperplasia, and endometrioid adenocarcinoma in postmenopausal women: a clinicopathological study of 238 cases|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0046817716302453|journal=Human Pathology|volume=59|pages=120–124|doi=10.1016/j.humpath.2016.09.021}}</ref> Women with hyperthecosis often have more markedly elevated testosterone, more hirsutism, and are much more likely to be virilized.<ref>http://www.uptodate.com/contents/ovarian-hyperthecosis</ref> While elevated androgens in postmenopausal women is rare,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krug|first=Esther|last2=Berga|first2=Sarah L.|date=2002-01-01|title=Postmenopausal hyperthecosis: Functional dysregulation of androgenesis in climacteric ovary|url=https://jhu.pure.elsevier.com/en/publications/postmenopausal-hyperthecosis-functional-dysregulation-of-androgen-3|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|language=en|volume=99|issue=5 SUPPL. 1|doi=10.1016/S0029-7844(01)01588-5|issn=0029-7844|pages=893–897}}</ref> hyperthecosis can present in both premenopausal or postmenopausal women. Women with hyperthecosis may or may not have always had underlying PCOS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://press.endocrine.org/doi/10.1210/MTP5.9781943550043.ch57|title=Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome : 2016 Meet-The-Professor: Endocrine Case Management|last=Wierman, MD|first=Margaret|date=2016|website=|language=en|doi=10.1210/mtp5.9781943550043.ch57|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref>
== Cause == The etiology of hyperthecosis is unknown, however evidence suggests a possibility of genetic transmission. Hyperthecosis has been documented in familiar patterns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/21998336_Hyperthecosis_an_inheritable_form_of_polycystic_ovarian_disease|title=Hyperthecosis: an inheritable form of polycystic ovarian disease|last=Wilroy|first=R.S.|date=February 1975|website=ResearchGate|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref> [[Insulin resistance]] may also play a role in the pathogenesis of hyperthecosis. Women with hyperthecosis have a significant degree of insulin resistance and insulin may stimulate the ovarian stromal androgen synthesis.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0002937886906769|title=Hyperinsulinemia in hyperthecosis of the ovaries |last=Nagamani M.D.|first=Manubai|date=February 1986|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-03|doi=10.1016/0002-9378(86)90676-9|volume=154|journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology|pages=384–389}}</ref>
== Prognosis == Although no large studies showing the long term outcomes for women with hyperthecosis exist, a diagnosis of hyperthecosis may suggest an increased risk for metabolic complications of [[hyperlipidemia]] and [[type 2 diabetes]] .<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rothman|first=Micol S.|last2=Wierman|first2=Margaret E.|date=2011-08-01|title=How should postmenopausal androgen excess be evaluated?|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-2265.2011.04040.x/abstract|journal=Clinical Endocrinology|language=en|volume=75|issue=2|pages=160–164|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2265.2011.04040.x|issn=1365-2265}}</ref> In postmenopausal women, hyperthecosis may also contribute to the pathogenesis of endometrial polyp, endometrial hyperplasia, and endometrioid adenocarcinoma due to the association of hyperestrinism (excess estrins in the body) and hyperthecosis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Cunxian|last2=Sung|first2=C. James|last3=Quddus|first3=M. Ruhul|last4=Simon|first4=Rochelle A.|last5=Jazaerly|first5=Tarek|last6=Lawrence|first6=W. Dwayne|date=2017-01-01|title=Association of ovarian hyperthecosis with endometrial polyp, endometrial hyperplasia, and endometrioid adenocarcinoma in postmenopausal women: a clinicopathological study of 238 cases|url=http://www.humanpathol.com/article/S0046-8177(16)30245-3/fulltext|journal=Human Pathology|language=English|volume=59|pages=120–124|doi=10.1016/j.humpath.2016.09.021|issn=0046-8177}}</ref> Treatment for hyperthecosis is based upon each case, but may range from pharmacological interventions to surgical.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krug|first=Esther|last2=Berga|first2=Sarah L.|date=2002-01-01|title=Postmenopausal hyperthecosis: Functional dysregulation of androgenesis in climacteric ovary|url=https://jhu.pure.elsevier.com/en/publications/postmenopausal-hyperthecosis-functional-dysregulation-of-androgen-3|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|language=en|volume=99|issue=5 SUPPL. 1|doi=10.1016/S0029-7844(01)01588-5|issn=0029-7844|pages=893–897}}</ref>
