{{short description|Term denoting a mental state}}
According to the [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Bradd Shore]], the '''''neuromantic'''''<ref name=":0">{{Citation|last=Shore|first=Bradd|title=Culture in Mind: Cognition, Culture, and the Problem of Meaning|url=|volume=|pages=141, 143–4|year=1996|location=|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=|isbn=|id=|authorlink=Bradd Shore|coauthors=}}</ref> refers to the cybernetic frame of mind among excited computer enthusiasts as they experience what Michael Heim called "the all-at-once simultaneity of totalizing presentness".<ref>{{Citation | last = Heim | first = Michael | authorlink = Michael R. Heim | coauthors = | title = Electric Language: A Philosophical Study of Word Processing | publisher = New Haven, CT: Yale University Press | year = 1987 | location = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | page = }}</ref> It is part of Shore's discourse on the embodied cognitive dimensions of the cultural transformation produced by the emergence of word processing, which he maintained has overcome the spatial limitations of the written text since "text modules can be combined, reconfigured, reduced, expanded, appended, or deleted from other units at the touch of a finger."<ref name=":0" /> This phenomenon is said to elicit passion that is also identified as an impulse unique to the modern world. Shore explains that "the sense of mastery over language resources that word processing bestows on the experienced user is intimately related to [[Martin Heidegger]]'s notion of [[Gestell|enframing ''(Bestellen'')]], a subjection of the world to human will that Heidegger saw as a characteristic of all modern technology."<ref>{{Citation | last = Heidegger | first = Martin | authorlink = Martin Heidegger | coauthors = | title = The Question Concerning Technology and Other Essays | publisher = New York: Harper & Row | year = 1977 | location = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | page = }}</ref>
There are sources that claim the concept of neuromantic is not only confined to computer enthusiasts. For instance, there is the so-called neuromantic imagination that inspire architects. Here, the cybernetic frame of mind is fired by the concept of the "third nature," which is occupied by those who inhabit not the actual terrain in which we live, work, and play but the virtual space of media flows that enter the "unconscious".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teletechnologies, Place, and Community|last=Wilken|first=Rowan|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=9780415875950|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> See also [[Flow (psychology)|Flowstates]].
